  "chunk_index": 33,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot receives a phone call from Maud Williams, who requests a meeting at the post office. While walking toward the post office, Poirot encounters Sergeant Fletcher, who has been conducting a search at the Manor House for Inspector Spence. Fletcher reveals that while no secret drawers were found, he discovered an old book containing the name \"Evelyn Hope\" written in pencil on the title page. Poirot recognizes this as the name Eva Kane used when she left England.\n\nAt the post office, Maud Williams informs Poirot that she witnessed an individual, dressed like a man in an old felt hat, attempting to climb through Mrs. Weatherby’s window using a gardener's ladder. The intruder fled when Maud saw them. Maud also confirms that \"Evelyn Hope\" was the name used by a woman who went to Australia, as reported in *The Sunday Comet*. This connection leads Maud to conclude that a person named Michael was correct regarding a previous theory.\n\nLater, Evelyn Carrington approaches Poirot to hire him. She is distressed because the police suspect her of killing Mrs. Upward. She admits to attempting to bribe the Croftes to provide a false alibi, claiming she was home listening to the radio during the crime, though the Croftes refused. Evelyn also reveals that Mrs. Upward had sent a message via Croft requesting a visit that evening, a request Evelyn had intended to ignore.",
